,"ATP","Glucose","Glycogen"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring alcohol metabolism, \u003Cstrong\u003ENAD+\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily depleted. Alcohol is first converted to acetaldehyde by alcohol dehydrogenase, and then to acetate by aldehyde dehydrogenase. Both of these reactions require NAD+ as a cofactor, converting it to NADH. The increased NADH/NAD+ ratio inhibits fatty acid oxidation and promotes fatty acid synthesis, leading to the accumulation of fat in the liver, known as fatty liver disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Eacetyl CoA\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in metabolism, it is not directly depleted by alcohol metabolism\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EATP\u003C/strong\u003E is not directly affected by alcohol metabolism in the context of fatty liver disease\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucose\u003C/strong\u003E levels are not directly depleted by alcohol metabolism\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlycogen\u003C/strong\u003E stores are not directly affected by alcohol metabolism\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Alcohol metabolism primarily depletes NAD+ in the liver, which is crucial for fatty acid oxidation.","The depletion of NAD+ leads to an accumulation of fatty acids, contributing to fatty liver disease.","Alcohol is metabolised in the liver by alcohol dehydrogenase and aldehyde dehydrogenase, both of which use NAD+ as a cofactor."],"references":["Gilbert-Barness, E., Barness, L. A., \u0026 Farrell, P. M. (Eds.). (2017). Metabolic diseases: foundations of clinical management, genetics, and pathology. IOS Press","Lanham-New, S. A., Macdonald, I. A., \u0026 Roche, H. M. (Eds.). (2011). Nutrition and metabolism. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Roche, H. M., Macdonald, I. A., Schols, A. M., \u0026 Lanham-New, S. A. (Eds.). (2024). Nutrition and metabolism. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Omiecinski CJ, Vanden Heuvel JP, Perdew GH, Peters JM. Xenobiotic metabolism, disposition, and regulation by receptors: from biochemical phenomenon to predictors of major toxicities. Toxicol Sci. 2011 Mar;120 Suppl 1(Suppl 1):S49-75. doi: 10.1093/toxsci/kfq338. Epub 2010 Nov 8. PMID: 21059794; PMCID: PMC3145385","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79516"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17982"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79516","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79516"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-03T12:43:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-03T12:45:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10696"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96901"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student